Date: 0/0/1966
Source: English Language in Aust. & NZ, The
Author: TURNER
Vol / Page: 160
Edition:
Quote: <i>Bush-line</i> or sometimes [161] <i>forest-line</i> (for American <i>timber-line</i>, English<i> tree-line </i>and Australian <i>tree-line</i> or <i>forest-line), bush-clad, bush burns</i> (areas where the bush has recently been burnt off) are tramping as well as general terms, as is the use of <i>shingle</i> for angular as well as rounded stones in <i>shingle slide</i>, or (earlier) <i>shingle slip</i>, also recently called scree as in Scotland and northern England. eg. 1890-1910 Ac. Loose, rather sharp, shale or similar rock. Much more widely used in NZ than C.O.D. `small rounded pebbles on sea-shore', esp. in loose combinations, or attributively eg shingle tops, basins, facings etc (Ac)
